A versatile variety of shapes are included: rectangular prisms, cubes, cylinders, half circles, arches, and two different sizes of rectangular planks and triangles. A set of wooden blocks provides an opportunity for a child to pass the hours constructing towers, castles, towns, and more; Designed for children ages 2 and up, this set offers the opportunity for younger kids to practice their fine motor skills and experiment with the laws of physics while giving older kids an outlet for their creativity. Parents will appreciate the safe, durable construction. Though they're made of solid wood, these blocks are light in weight, which makes them safer for small children. The blocks have rounded edges and a smooth painted finish that won't splinter with play. Our wooden building blocks set is designed for kids entertainment but also introduces early math concepts, and helps children develop good patience and strong motor skills. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 7, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Endless Possibilities with Melissa & Doug Wooden Building Set!
reviews.reviewText: Alright, let's talk about the Melissa & Doug Wooden Building Set - 100 Blocks in 4 Colors and 9 Shapes. As a parent always on the lookout for toys that spark imagination and creativity, this set has exceeded all expectations!First off, let's talk about the quality. These blocks are beautifully crafted from wood, with smooth edges that are safe for little hands. The colors are vibrant and the shapes are varied, offering endless opportunities for exploration and building.Now, onto the fun part: building! My kids have been absolutely obsessed with this set since the moment it arrived. From simple towers to elaborate structures, their imagination knows no bounds. And as a parent, there's nothing more heartwarming than watching them work together to create something truly amazing.But here's what sets this set apart: it's not just about building. These blocks also encourage learning through play. Whether it's counting the blocks, identifying colors, or sorting shapes, there's so much educational value packed into every play session.And can we talk about the versatility? With 100 blocks in 4 colors and 9 shapes, the possibilities are endless. My kids never get bored because there's always something new to create.Plus, the storage crate is a game-changer. Not only does it keep all the blocks organized, but it also makes cleanup a breeze. No more scattered blocks all over the floor - hallelujah!In summary, if you're looking for a timeless toy that will provide hours of entertainment, foster creativity, and promote learning, then the Melissa & Doug Wooden Building Set is an absolute must-have. Trust me, your kids will thank you for it (and you might just find yourself joining in on the fun too)!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on March 4, 2016
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Small, but good!
reviews.reviewText: After a few months of my 3 year old playing with these, I'm going to give this 4 stars.The biggest reason is they are pretty small. It's a LOT of blocks, but it's a lot of small blocks, which are difficult if not impossible to build with on our fluffy shaggy carpeting. It's not the end of the world, which is why I still am giving it 4 stars, but it can be frustrating for him. Which means it's frustrating for me. We just give him a big book to use as a base and that's alright, but I'd caution against buying this for a very young child who still puts things in their mouth or who gets frustrated easily...The box they come in is not really great for storage, so be prepared to transfer them to another bin if these get played with regularly. It just doesn't hold up.Other than being small and the not-good-for-long box, my son loves these blocks. He pretends they are food and pretends to cook them, he plants "gardens" full of blocks, and of course builds pretty great buildings. The colors are bright and slightly glossy, and the paint is holding up very well so far, but if your kid is still chewing on their toys I don't think the paint would last long. They are also uniform in size and fit together nicely without gaps. There are no warped pieces or wonky pieces that might make a builder frustrated.Also, someone mentioned something about a prop 65 warning... check out the list of chemicals online at OEHHA.ca.gov before you get too worked up. There are some pretty bizarre rules about what gets a warning (only one agency has to deem it dangerous; there's no checks/balances. It also doesn't take into account different states of the chemical; somethings are only hazardous when inhaled as an aerosol, but if it's dry paint they still might list it on the package. It's also entirely up to businesses to use their discretion in adding a prop 65 warning, so sometimes I imagine it's a "better safe than sorry" scenario). It might be as simple as the plastic handle attached to the box contains pthalates. Or that there could be wood dust in the box (true story, wood dust is on the list for causing cancer). In which case, a warning would need to be issued. On the Melissa and Doug website they have a whole page about safety and their testing requirements, especially regarding paint.Anyway. These are a very nice, quality made children's toy and the only reason I don' t despise picking up all 100 of them daily is that my son loves them.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 15, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A delight for toddlers!
reviews.reviewText: My nephews are 2 and 3 years old. We brought these out and they lost their minds with excitement ready to play! They're colorful and all different shapes, and not too big for tiny hands. Toys like this really bring out the creative and logical skills for people of all ages. I loved playing with them too!

I've had them for 8ish months and they're holding up well to daily use. There are no paint chips or anything (aside from the one that ended up in the shower and got all discoloured), they're the great classic shapes, good for building all sorts of shapes and all ages. I use them with my 2 and 4 year old to build towers and cities and snakes. If you're playing with more than one child I'd recommend getting 2 sets.

The toddlers can use it in any way they want. Whether it is for building or sorting colors or sorting shapes or counting numbers. It leaves a lot of room for imaginative play. I would highly recommend this toy.
